metadata.name: Ecce Gratum #2
metadata.description:
"Ecce Gratum" is a symphony of colors and lines, a visual work that sings to the soul. The strokes of the brush are bold and confident, yet gentle and loving, like the notes of a symphony. The title, "Ecce Gratum", translates to "Behold the pleasing", and as you gaze upon this art, it is impossible not to be moved by its beauty and wonder. This painting is a celebration of life, a reminder to embrace the present and to find joy in the simple things. It is a call to look beyond the surface, to see the beauty in the world around us, and to let our hearts sing

[S] on live view to save a png

metadata.name: Cracks #2
metadata.description: I’m interested in people’s darker side, the ones that aren’t easy and well balanced. The cracks.

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #19
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

metadata.name: Sands of Time #334
metadata.description:
We've been recently inspired to do this work while being on vacation, in one the most vibrant cities in the world, in the hot pot and intermixture of cultures, terrains and soundscapes. Borrowing the metaphors of sand, from Negarestani's "Cyclonopedia", and of time from "Chronosis", these living substances, we wanted to represent some of the vibes, that have been implanted into our gritty enduring nomadic existence.

This work was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine
- #Tezos4Iran

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

November, 2022

metadata.name: terrains #40
metadata.description:
A generative set of imaginary landscapes.

Terrains continues a study of topographic media translations that began with Plastic Landscapes (2016) and our Field Guide to Martian Landscapes (2017). While the Field Guide focused on analyzing topographies of another planet, interpreted through telescopic imaging and software translation, this project focuses on the procedural generation of nonexistent landscapes. These landscapes are generated through a complex manipulation of perlin noise, a recurring algorithm used in videogames, film VFX, and generative art since the 1980s that resembles natural geological formations. By no means new, this tradition is part of a lineage of digital visualization projects focused on reproducing nature through algorithmic means. Our algorithm generates sequential bands of noise mapped on an X-Y plane, rendered in an oblique architectural projection, a techniques that comes from technical drawing conventions. This perspective produces a layering effect that flattens the terrain in an architectural way. Neither realistic nor completely abstract, the system plays with projection, entropy, and constraints to produce a collection of imaginary terrains sited on the Tezos blockchain.

We must also credit all who have explored this field of work: Ken Perlin, James M. Bardeen, Stephen Schmitt, Paul Bourke, Joseph Claghorn, Amit Patel, Inigo Quilez, Matt DesLauriers, and many many more...

Press "s" to download PNG.
Press "r" to redraw and shift stripes.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2023

metadata.name: Make-believe #28
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: In Between #18
metadata.description:
In Between

Genuary is an artificially generated month of time where we build code that makes beautiful things, with 31 prompts to base your code art off. Genuary 2023 took place during the month of January 2023. Afterwards, as it happens, comes Genuary 32nd. This is an imaginary week, during which we develop one of our Genuary pieces into a 32 edition "not very long"-form generative project on fx(hash).

My Genuary 32nd project is based on Genuary 22nd: Shadows, the design of which again was based on the "art deco" pattern from day 20.

The patterns form a grid-like fence structure, dividing the space and creating an infinite cage. Light coming from the outside casts stark shadows on the floor. Several variations on halftoning techniques are used to portray tone, occasionally destroying depth perception into an abstract interplay of form.

The code of this piece has been diminished into a mere 3397 characters.

You can use the URL-parameter &m=2 as a resolution multiplier, to render images larger than your screen.

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma. https://piterpasma.nl

The goal of this design is to display angular ideas placed on natural elements like the moon and sea in the simplest way possible.
s = save

metadata.name: Acid Quilt #100
metadata.description:
This is an abstract work. There is no true or correct orientation.

Inspired by repeater patterns, tiles, tessellations, and quilts. Not as goofy as the Collage of Collage set but still some goofiness to it. This collage set is made up of layers sketched on a really old ipad. 

The project does not have a repeater functions built in, just produces the single base unit. My hope is that the output be used on a larger canvas and repeated, tiled, or tessellated. Some outputs might could look good in a quilt. 

These online tools (as of Feb 2022) are easy to use for making tiles. Windows also makes it easy to tile, as does Photoshop:
- https://www.imgonline.com.ua/eng/check-texture-tiling.php
- https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/gdiplus/-gdiplus-tiling-a-shape-with-an-image-use
- https://prinfab.com/printed-fabric?r2=magic

(^This^ is very much not a best practice, including links in this description that might not exist in the future)

There are more than 1.3 billion possible combos!

Please enjoy!

metadata.name: Pixel Tunnel II #428
metadata.description:
This is based on a technique I've used to create textured abstract art by starting with a base design and applying millions of small mutations. Each design has a minimum of 1,500,000 mutations.

This design is built in 2 phases.
Phase 1: Aggressive twisted pixel tunnels create a tangled root system.
Phase 2: Less aggressive straight lines break up the sharp root systems and make the colors blend together.

- Higher themes are more rare (50 max)
- Higher patterns are more rare (15 max)

metadata.name: Sabler #246
metadata.description:
'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self. 

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements. In line with that simplicity, colors and palettes have also been kept to a minimum.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.
